Opera Test

www.wisemapping.com/c/try.htm

Goal

Investigate the broken map on http://www.wisemapping.com/c/try.htm. If the site is indeed broken, create a minimal test case showing only the bug, nothing else, with a clear pass condition. Advise on how the issue, if valid, can be resolved.

Replicate

The first step was to replicate the bug. I first tested the site in Firefox 3.5.3 and Opera 10.52 (8333).

The bug is certainly valid. Having a quick inspection of the site, there were also some CSS formatting issues with the toolbar items hover state. Those weren't in the user's original bug report, so I ignored it. If I were working at Opera, I'd probably file a low priority bug just so we didn't forget about it.

Errors

I looked through Opera's error console to see if there were any unusual errors. Ignoring the wad of -moz and IE CSS hacks, two errors relating to negative CSS heights caught my eye.

Using Dragonfly, I checked to see if setting the height to a non-negative value displayed the map. The map was only partially visible. This was acceptable as the height value was probably used in many other calculations onload. Seeing part of the map meant that the issue didn't lie with the rendering of the map itself and was most likely a Javascript bug somewhere throughout the code.

I quickly scanned the DOM to confirm my suspicions. There weren't any height properties set (Unlike in Firefox), or else they were -151px. I also noticed that the graph adjusted to the browser's height so the problem was certainly somewhere in the page's Javascript.

Javascript

I pulled down the code using the command

$ wget -r -U "Opera/9.80 (Windows NT 6.1; U; en) Presto/2.5.22 \
  Version/10.50" http://www.wisemapping.com/c/try.htm

and additionally downloaded mindplot.svg.js so that I could experiment with the site on my local machine. I then checked this pristine copy into a temporary Git repository so I could make changes without loosing data.

I noticed that the value -151px was the result of -90 - 61 which appeared on line in editor.js:530. In Opera, the screenHeight was 0, but in Firefox it was the proper client Height. A quick console.log confirmed this. The screenHeight came from the following function:

window.getHeight = function() {
  if (this.webkit419) {
    return this.innerHeight
  }
  if (this.opera) {
    return document.body.clientHeight
  }
  return document.documentElement.clientHeight
}

They are using Opera specific Javascript. What they probably didn't realise is that document.body.clientHeight and document.documentElement.clientHeight are two very different properties on different elements. One is the height of the window, and the other is the height of the body (which is essentialy the height of all the content). If you are reading this in Opera the number below should be far larger than your client's height, which is px. In all other browsers the two numbers will be equal.

When the script is being called the body height is still zero as the body hasn't finished loading and many elements are still hidden. Though, this bug doesn't quite lend itself to a minimal test, I have produced a small file which will always return 0 in Opera and a number greater than zero otherwise. This shows the difference between the two elements. You can view it here.

Resolution

This isn't a rendering error in Opera. It conforms to the spec and Webkit and Gecko both exhibit this behaviour too. The creators of the site are inadvertently introducing a bug for Opera.

I recommend patching the website. The site isn't high profile enough to warrent an indiviual fix in Opera core. Also, as Opera conforms to the spec, there is no need to redefine it. The following diff gets the site working again:

Taking a philosophical detour, all code is a product of it's environment and often decisions which may look bad in retrospect were perfectly logical at the time. In this case, a previous version of Opera could have been causing the site problems and adding that conditional could have fixed the problem. As not to break this behaviour, and because the bug was only reported in Opera 10.5, I recommend adding a version check. I could find the exact version of Opera where the behaviour of document.documentElement.clientHeight didn't conform to spec, however that requires access the Opera bug tracker.
